- Saunders extraction candidates
    - format: per candidate, list chapter, location, paraphrase, situation, outcome
    - outcomes: → promoted to <slug>, → folded into <slug>, → dropped because <reason>

- Chapter 2: We Begin
    - location: lines 243, 247
    - paraphrase: after finishing a story, collect honest felt reactions and locate each one at a specific spot on the page, refusing literary jargon
    - situation: you have just finished reading a story and want to learn from it (as reader or writer) without skipping the diagnostic data your own reactions provide
    - outcome: → promoted to the-basic-drill

- Chapter 2: We Begin
    - location: line 241
    - paraphrase: when discussing or evaluating a story, shift the question from interpretive (what does X mean, what is X a metaphor for) to strategic (what is X doing for the reader, why do we need X)
    - situation: you are critiquing, teaching, revising, or workshopping a story and risk producing an interpretation that says nothing about how the story actually works
    - outcome: → promoted to ask-strategic-not-interpretive

- Chapter 2: We Begin
    - location: line 271
    - paraphrase: judge a craft model, theory, or slogan by whether it is helping you reach the desired state of mind, not by whether it is correct (finger pointing at the moon, criterion: is it helping)
    - situation: you encounter a piece of writing advice, theory, or model and have to decide whether to adopt it, debate it, or discard it
    - outcome: → promoted to is-it-helping

- Chapter 2: We Begin
    - location: lines 193, 197
    - paraphrase: keep a small set of touchstone stories as your high bar against which to measure your own work
    - situation: a writer wants an external standard for their own work
    - outcome: → dropped because the chapter mentions this in passing as autobiographical practice, with no concrete action, no observable signal, and no failure mode that distinguishes it from generic advice

- Chapter 2: We Begin
    - location: line 251
    - paraphrase: treat reading as workbook work, with intent to go deeper than a first read allows
    - situation: a reader wants more than a casual encounter with a story
    - outcome: → folded into the-basic-drill (the drill itself is the "deeper than first read" mechanism Saunders is naming)

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 329-368, 735-748 (the explicit three-question protocol, repeated)
    - paraphrase: at a chosen pause in a story-in-progress, answer three specific questions about reader-state (what do you know, what are you curious about, where do you think it's headed) and treat the answers as the data the rest of the story must use
    - situation: you are mid-read of a story, mid-revision of a draft, or trying to learn how a story is working on you, and you want to make the moment-by-moment effects visible
    - outcome: → promoted to page-break-diagnostic

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 569-595 (explicit procedure with iterative refinement of summary)
    - paraphrase: produce a one-sentence "Hollywood version" of what the story appears to want to be, then iteratively adjust toward greater specificity, treating each refinement as artillery fire
    - situation: a workshop, critique session, or revision pass where the group is about to start suggesting changes before agreeing what the story is trying to do
    - outcome: → promoted to hollywood-version

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 964-973 (named principle, tested against the teahouse scene)
    - paraphrase: every structural unit of a story must (1) be entertaining in its own right and (2) advance the story in a non-trivial way; test each scene against both
    - situation: revising or critiquing a draft, encountering a scene whose presence you suspect but can't justify
    - outcome: → promoted to cornfeld-principle

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 822-855 (Hanov removed; "ritual banality avoidance" named); lines 841-845 ("push the new bead to the knot")
    - paraphrase: identify the obvious or expected first-order resolution your story is gesturing toward, then deliberately remove that option to force the story past its original plane of conception
    - situation: drafting or revising and noticing that the story is heading toward the satisfying-but-predictable resolution your reader has already imagined
    - outcome: → promoted to ritual-banality-avoidance

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 711-723 (worsening road vs. improving road); lines 944-952 (rough teahouse vs. cheerful teahouse)
    - paraphrase: when you suspect a craft choice is working but can't say why, write or imagine the inverted version of the same element and hold the two side by side until the difference becomes nameable
    - situation: revising, teaching, or trying to learn from a sentence/description/scene whose effect you feel but can't articulate
    - outcome: → promoted to two-version-comparison

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 415-434 (specification through ruling out); lines 916-924 (Marya's specification continues at the teahouse)
    - paraphrase: when introducing or developing a character, ask "which particular person is this?" and answer with facts that rule out clichéd alternatives, narrowing the path until meaningful action becomes possible
    - situation: drafting a story whose character feels generic or whose plot won't move because the character lacks traction
    - outcome: → promoted to increasing-specification

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 1130-1152 (truncate "In the Cart" and ask "Is it story yet?")
    - paraphrase: when judging whether a story is finished or what its ending is doing, experimentally cut the last section, read up to the cut, and observe what feels missing
    - situation: revising your own draft, or studying another story, and trying to isolate what the ending is supplying
    - outcome: → promoted to truncation-test

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 305-316, 368-378 ("expectation/resolution moments," juggler/bowling pins, curiosity-as-caring)
    - paraphrase: read each line as creating expectations the next must satisfy or complicate; track which "pins" are in the air
    - situation: any close reading
    - outcome: → folded into the-page-break-diagnostic (the procedural form Saunders gives this idea is the three-question protocol; the bowling pins are vocabulary for what the protocol surfaces)

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 1068-1082 (variation in Semyon's gossip beats; against stasis)
    - paraphrase: when a character or pattern recurs, alter at least one parameter so the second occurrence is not a static repeat of the first
    - situation: drafting and noticing a beat is about to repeat itself
    - outcome: → dropped because the procedural form is too vague (action: "vary it"), with no concrete signal that distinguishes good variation from random change; the underlying caution is captured by increasing-specification (don't let a character stay static)

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 627-633 (Hanov as warm-but-clueless; broad type cross-painted with contradictory info)
    - paraphrase: when introducing a character of a recognizable type, set up the type, then complicate it with a contradictory trait to produce three-dimensionality
    - situation: drafting a character whose type the reader will pattern-match
    - outcome: → folded into increasing-specification (cross-painting is one technique within the larger move of ruling out clichéd possibilities)

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 1331-1336 (motorcycle/sidecar metaphor for reader-writer closeness)
    - paraphrase: keep emotional distance between reader and protagonist small enough that the reader follows the character into whatever happens
    - situation: drafting, especially endings that ask the reader to absorb a difficult turn
    - outcome: → dropped because the chapter offers it as an evocative model, not a procedure; the action is too vague (no concrete way to measure or control "distance"); the closest concrete moves are already captured by increasing-specification and the page-break diagnostic

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 497-512 (structure as call-and-response, story raises questions and answers them)
    - paraphrase: think of structure as the organizational scheme by which a story answers the questions it has caused its reader to ask
    - situation: analyzing or revising a story's overall shape
    - outcome: → folded into the-page-break-diagnostic (the questions a story has caused the reader to ask ARE what the diagnostic surfaces; the answer to "what is structure?" reduces to "the call-and-response between questions surfaced page by page and what the story does next")

- Chapter 4: Afterthought #1
    - location: lines 1355-1359 (Cat in the Rain classroom procedure: cut the story into 200-word "pages," ask the three questions per page, then truncate near the end and ask "Is it story yet?")
    - paraphrase: a teacher's recipe for running the page-at-a-time exercise on a fresh story by physically cutting it into pages
    - situation: a teacher running the exercise on a new short story in a class period
    - outcome: → folded into page-break-diagnostic and truncation-test (this is a packaging of the same two procedures applied to a different story; no new procedural content)

- Chapter 4: Afterthought #1
    - location: lines 1369-1377 ("a story is a series of incremental pulses... criticism is just (1) noticing ourselves responding moment by moment and (2) getting better at articulating that response")
    - paraphrase: a one-paragraph restatement of the line-by-line ethos: criticism is reaction-noticing plus reaction-articulating
    - situation: a reader who has finished a story and wants to learn from it
    - outcome: → folded into the-basic-drill (this is exactly the basic drill restated; "incremental pulses" overlaps with page-break-diagnostic; no novel procedure)

- Chapter 4: Afterthought #1
    - location: lines 1375-1377 (Hemingway's "built-in, shockproof, shit detector"; the deep, honest part of the mind reacts and that part is what reading and writing refine)
    - paraphrase: trust the deep honest reaction of the mind as a quality detector; reading and writing refine that faculty
    - situation: any reader/writer judging quality
    - outcome: → folded into the-basic-drill (this is a vivid name for the same diagnostic stance: any honest reaction is valid data; the move is unchanged)

- Chapter 4: Afterthought #1
    - location: lines 1387-1401 (Bicycle Thieves sequence audit: trees, the truck of fans, the wallet check, the loving couple in the background; "an artist takes responsibility for every single thing")
    - paraphrase: audit a composed unit (paragraph, scene, frame) element by element, asking what each one is doing for the reader; every element must have either a stated function or an explicit decision to keep it as atmosphere
    - situation: revising a unit where you suspect some details are there by default rather than by intent
    - outcome: → promoted to take-responsibility-for-every-element

- Chapter 4: Afterthought #1
    - location: line 1401 ("that's what an artist does: takes responsibility")
    - paraphrase: the disposition of taking responsibility for every choice in the work
    - situation: the artist's general stance toward their work
    - outcome: → folded into take-responsibility-for-every-element (this is the disposition the audit procedure operationalizes; not a separate move)

- Chapter 5: The Singers (Turgenev source story)
    - location: lines 1407-1635 (entire chapter)
    - paraphrase: no candidates. The chapter is Turgenev's story as Saunders presents it, with no Saunders commentary. Notable structural moves are visible (extended village/character portraits inserted between contest buildup and the contest itself; Yashka's transcendent song followed by a deflationary drunken-aftermath scene; narrator's choice to exit at the peak; the closing fade of the "Antropka" call across the valley) but none of these can be promoted to a skill from the story alone without leaning on Chapter 6's forthcoming commentary, which is out of scope for this pass.
    - situation: not applicable
    - outcome: → none promoted; the story is data the next chapter will use to teach moves about narrative structure and "the heart of the story"

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 1656-1666 (TICHN cart, transactional reading state, "create a pattern of excesses and convert them into virtues")
    - paraphrase: while reading or revising, log non-normative features (presentational excesses) the writer is asking the reader to tolerate, then track whether the rest of the work redeems each one
    - situation: reading a story whose surface contains conspicuous oddities, or revising a draft where you want to tell which excesses are doing work and which are unredeemed
    - outcome: → promoted to track-non-normative-excesses

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 1676-1694, 1782-1854 ("What is the heart of you, dear story?", candy-factory and Club-Story-bouncer images, the worked tabulation of the eleven pre-contest pages)
    - paraphrase: name the central event the rest of the story should be serving (the heart), then walk through every other part asking what it does for that heart
    - situation: revising or critiquing a draft that feels long or off-center but you cannot say what specific section is failing against what reference point
    - outcome: → promoted to heart-of-the-story

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 1924-1938 (side characters as "an ascending ladder of credibility" during the contest; the texting-friends-from-the-opera analogy)
    - paraphrase: when the central event of a story cannot be directly experienced by the reader (a song, a sermon, a dance), set up multiple side characters with established and differing credibilities so their graded reactions adjudicate the event for the reader
    - situation: drafting or revising a scene whose central event is unwitnessable on the page
    - outcome: → promoted to panel-of-judges

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 2002-2038 (the "holding up against" exercise; the two-trees painting analogy; the demonstration on the ravine and on the rooks/crows/sparrows)
    - paraphrase: take an apparently static element (a setting, an image, a digression) and juxtapose it mentally with the heart of the story; the immediate non-articulate response (relation found / not found) is the data, and articulation of the relation surfaces structural patterns (binaries, foreshadowed contrasts) the rest of the story is also organized by
    - situation: noticing an apparently decorative element that you suspect is structurally loaded but cannot articulate
    - outcome: → promoted to holding-up-against-the-heart

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 2064-2130 (wrist-meter / 1000 energy units; Olympic-sprinter-becomes-shotputter; "Hemingway Mountain" vs. "Saunders Mountain"; the autobiographical Seussian-poems-and-cartoons moment)
    - paraphrase: judge your own writing voice by the energy it generates in readers, not by whether it is the voice of the writer you wanted to be; when the energetic voice turns out to be a smaller, embarrassing one, commit to it
    - situation: a writer producing technically careful work in an aspired-to mode that elicits "interesting" rather than "alive" reactions
    - outcome: → promoted to energy-not-aspiration

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 1704-1712 (A vs. B contest needs the contestants to "stand for something" so the outcome is meaningful)
    - paraphrase: in a story built on a contest of skills, A and B must each represent something distinct so the outcome can carry meaning
    - situation: drafting or revising a contest-shaped story where the outcome currently feels arbitrary
    - outcome: → folded into increasing-specification (this is increasing-specification applied at the level of contest stakes; the underlying move is the same — make each contestant a particular person who stands for something so action becomes meaningful — and Ch 6 sharpens the trigger to "your contest outcome feels arbitrary because A and B do not yet stand for distinct things")

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 1730-1736 (reading fiction as "a series of establishings, stabilizations, and alterations")
    - paraphrase: every reading experience is a sequence of establishings ("the dog is sleeping"), stabilizations ("he is sleeping deeply"), and alterations ("he woke up")
    - situation: any close reading
    - outcome: → folded into page-break-diagnostic (this is the same beat-tracking the three-question protocol surfaces, restated in a different vocabulary; no new procedural content)

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: line 1748 ("specificity makes character")
    - paraphrase: a single specific way of doing the thing makes the character a particular person who stands for something
    - situation: drafting a character who currently feels generic
    - outcome: → folded into increasing-specification (this is the principle that skill operationalizes; the contest-specific application is captured by the fold above)

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 1944-1946 (the "cut the story by 20% then 10% more" classroom assignment)
    - paraphrase: photocopy a published story and cut it down to a contemporary pace until you start cutting into the bone; learn touch by trimming someone else's work
    - situation: a writer who needs to develop the cutting instinct
    - outcome: → dropped because this is a teaching exercise, not a procedure with an observable signal or a recognizable failure mode that distinguishes good cutting from bad; the underlying ability ("touch") is named but not operationalized; Saunders himself frames it as a recommendation rather than a method (the deeper work of "what cuts" is captured by cornfeld-principle and take-responsibility-for-every-element). Note: Appendix A (Ch 24) is an actual cutting exercise and may surface a procedural skill on its own terms.

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 2140-2146 ("the blessing an artist gives the final product is his way of saying that he approves of everything within it"; pausing in the doorway, seeing nothing more to change)
    - paraphrase: the artist's final approval comes by letting the work stand and sending it out; you stop tinkering when nothing in the room asks to be changed
    - situation: late-stage revision when you suspect the work is done but keep adjusting
    - outcome: → folded into take-responsibility-for-every-element (the disposition of "approving everything within it" is the disposition that skill operationalizes; the "letting it stand" stopping rule is its terminal condition)

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 1690 ("the Hollywood version" of "The Singers": "Two men have a singing contest in a Russian pub. One wins, one loses.")
    - paraphrase: brief restatement of hollywood-version applied to "The Singers"
    - situation: any teaching of the hollywood-version move
    - outcome: → folded into hollywood-version (a second worked instance of the same move; no new procedural content)

- Chapter 7: Afterthought #2
    - location: lines 2199-2203 (P/N meter on the forehead, instantaneous fix at every needle-drop, lather/rinse/repeat across hundreds of drafts), 2213-2217 (block-level "undeniability"; blocks start telling you their order), 2229-2237 (felt-not-decided; "intuition plus iteration"; "given infinite time, anything can happen"), 2247-2253 (apartment redecoration metaphor: hundreds of versions of you contributing one cut/swap per day), 2261-2267 (seed crystal; "overturning the tyranny of the first draft"; you don't need an idea, just a sentence)
    - paraphrase: revise by repeatedly reading the draft fresh as a first-time reader would, watching for an instinctive negative reaction at the line level, making the small fix that comes to mind, then doing it again, hundreds or thousands of times; the story shapes itself by accreted micro-decisions rather than top-down planning
    - situation: a writer revising a draft who keeps trying to plan the story's meaning, structure, or theme top-down, or who is paralyzed because the first draft is not good enough to start work on
    - outcome: → promoted to iterative-preference-revision

- Chapter 7: Afterthought #2
    - location: lines 2291-2303 (the Jane sentence reduced to "Jane" by asking why each element is needed), 2313-2335 (the Jim/Sara cut, removing what is contained in the action of dropping the keys; "the latter version has more respect for you, the reader, built into it"), 2337-2345 (story as frank conversation between equals; the writer imagines the reader as intelligent and worldly)
    - paraphrase: when revising, cut anything the reader can supply for themselves from what is already on the page; assume an intelligent reader and remove the parts that explain what the action or context already conveys
    - situation: revising prose that explains, narrates emotional reaction, or restates what an action already shows; the passage feels belabored even though no individual sentence is wrong
    - outcome: → promoted to respect-the-reader-cut

- Chapter 7: Afterthought #2
    - location: lines 2269-2281 ("Bob was an asshole" iteratively specified into "Bob snapped impatiently at the young barista, who reminded him of his dead wife..."; the unintended moral-ethical effect of specification)
    - paraphrase: when a flat or generic statement appears in your prose, revise it through successive rounds of "why" until the flat statement becomes a particular human moment; the moral richness emerges as a side effect of the specification, not as the goal
    - situation: revising a sentence that states a verdict on a character (he was an asshole, she was sad, they were happy) instead of rendering the moment that produced the verdict
    - outcome: → folded into increasing-specification (the move is the same — ask why, add a fact that rules out the generic version, repeat — applied to a single sentence rather than to a character introduction; Ch 7 supplies the moral-ethical side-effect framing and the prose-line worked example)

- Chapter 7: Afterthought #2
    - location: lines 2229, 2231-2233 ("when I'm writing well, there's almost no intellectual/analytical thinking going on"; the relief of not having to decide; willing to make playful changes at the line level knowing the next read offers a chance to revert)
    - paraphrase: a stance of trusting felt impulse rather than analysis during revision; you don't have to commit to a change because the next pass can undo it
    - situation: writers who feel paralyzed by every revision decision because they treat each change as final
    - outcome: → folded into iterative-preference-revision (this is the disposition that makes the iterative method work; the skill operationalizes it via "make the change now, knowing the next pass can revert")

- Chapter 7: Afterthought #2
    - location: lines 2183-2189 (Stan and the model railroad: hobo posture, turning the plastic woman, "all art begins in that instant of intuitive preference")
    - paraphrase: art begins in pre-articulate preference, the small "yes" that occurs before language; trust the impulse before trying to explain it
    - situation: any moment of artistic adjustment
    - outcome: → folded into iterative-preference-revision (the Stan story is the chapter's opening illustration of the same move the skill operationalizes; the "instant of intuitive preference" is the felt event the P/N meter trains you to notice)

- Chapter 8: The Darling (Chekhov source story)
    - location: lines 2351-2542 (entire chapter)
    - paraphrase: no candidates. The chapter is Chekhov's story as Saunders presents it, with no Saunders commentary. Visible structural features include the four-attachment pattern (papa and aunt and French teacher in childhood, then Kukin the theater manager, then Pustovalov the lumberyard manager, then Smirnin the veterinary, then finally the boy Sasha), the repeated mechanism by which Olenka takes on each partner's vocabulary and opinions as her own, the deflated middle stretch in which she has no one and consequently no opinions at all, the loud structural rhyme between the late-night telegram-knock that announces Kukin's death and the late-night knock that turns out to be the veterinary returning from the club at the end, and the way the closing Sasha attachment is set apart from the prior three by the narrator's explicit comment that none of her former attachments was as deep. Each is a teachable feature in principle, but the procedural form (action, observable signal, named failure mode) cannot be articulated honestly from the story alone without anticipating Chapter 9's commentary, which is out of scope for this pass.
    - situation: not applicable
    - outcome: → none promoted; the story is data the next chapter (titled "A Pattern Story") will use to teach moves about repetition-as-pattern, identity through relationship, and how a story differentiates a final repetition from earlier ones

- Chapter 9: A Pattern Story
    - location: lines 2587, 2777-2787, 2906-2918, 2966-2972, 2982-2993 (Table 2 introduced, Tables 2-3 paralleled across the four loves, football-choreography internal-dynamics analogy, the pattern-disruption-and-honoring of Vasily's deferred death, the read-across-rows diagnostic that surfaces decline)
    - paraphrase: when a story repeats a scene-type, relationship, or unit, fix a shared schema of parameters (job, courtship, flavor, address-form, duration, parting, mourning, ...) on the first instance and carry it forward for every subsequent instance, then read across each row to surface the controlled variation; the same procedure is the writer's drafting tool (vary every parameter mindfully) and the reader's diagnostic tool (variation across rows is the inferred meaning)
    - situation: drafting or revising a story whose structure repeats a scene-type or relationship type and you suspect the recurrences are reading as either flat (no variation, anecdote not story) or random (variation without pattern); or critiquing a story to surface what its repetitions are telling you
    - outcome: → promoted to parameter-table-for-recurrence

- Chapter 9: A Pattern Story
    - location: lines 3046-3072 (Always be escalating; "refuse to repeat beats"; the within-the-beat diagnosis; reading ahead to find the next nudge of escalation; ending where Sasha's resistance escalates from "leave me alone" to the dream of violence)
    - paraphrase: once a beat has occurred (a fundamental change in the character's state), do not stay there elaborating on that state; locate where in the prose you are still inside the just-changed condition, and find the next nudge that pushes the character (or the meaning) into a new state; "always be escalating"
    - situation: revising or critiquing a draft where you can feel a section is stalling, the prose is occupying a settled state for pages even though no individual sentence is wrong, you sense restlessness but cannot say what is missing
    - outcome: → promoted to refuse-to-repeat-beats

- Chapter 9: A Pattern Story
    - location: lines 2693-2698 (Chekhov leaps over the ninety-odd post-funeral days because they are not meaningful; "by whose standard? The story's"; the bold leap teaches that the short story is not a documentary or a fair-minded accounting but a radically shaped little machine)
    - paraphrase: when the story has nothing meaningful to do with a stretch of in-world time, leap over it; the test is not how long the elapsed time is in the world but whether the story has work to do during it; resist the calendar-tending impulse that writes "On Wednesday she did the washing"
    - situation: drafting or revising a stretch of narrative time during which nothing the story cares about is happening, you are about to cover the days because they happened, you feel the prose flatlining
    - outcome: → promoted to skip-the-meaningless-interval

- Chapter 9: A Pattern Story
    - location: lines 3000-3022 (the Trot-the-cat moment as an inflection point; "Is this better, or this?"; Chekhov rejects the first-order option and supplies Sasha; line 3022 explicitly says "as in 'In the Cart,' the removal of the first-order option forces the story to supply something better")
    - paraphrase: at the moment the story expects an obvious next move (Olenka loves the cat), pause and ask the optometrist's question "Is this better, or this?" comparing the obvious option against rejecting it for something richer
    - situation: drafting at a moment where the story can deliver the expected next thing or refuse it
    - outcome: → folded into ritual-banality-avoidance (Saunders himself names this as the same Hanov-removal procedure from "In the Cart"; the optometrist's "Is this better or this?" formulation is a sharper trigger and the Trot-rejection is a second worked instance of the same first-order-removal move)

- Chapter 9: A Pattern Story
    - location: lines 2747-2767 (the Mel/Dr. Bukhari sentence iteratively specified from "some guy is sitting in a random room" through "an angry racist" to "an angry white racist named Mel, who has cancer..."; "in specificity lies nascent plot")
    - paraphrase: Saunders restates the increasing-specification move at the sentence level using a fresh worked example, framing it in the claim that specificity precedes plot
    - situation: drafting a sentence whose situation is too generic for action to need to happen
    - outcome: → folded into increasing-specification (this is a third worked instance of the same move at sentence scope, alongside the existing "Bob was an asshole" instance from Ch 7; Ch 9's sharpening is the explicit slogan "in specificity lies nascent plot" — specificity does not just add color, it produces the conditions under which meaningful action can occur)

- Chapter 9: A Pattern Story
    - location: lines 3068-3104 (the late-night knock at the gate at the end echoes the late-night knock at the gate that announced Kukin's death; the structural rhyme tells the reader, before the content does, that "Olenka's beloved is about to be taken away" — and then the rhyme is honored differently when the knock turns out to be Smirnin home from the club)
    - paraphrase: when an earlier moment in a story has a recognizable shape (a knock at the gate at night), echo that shape near the end so the reader's pattern-recognition fires, then either fulfill or invert the expectation
    - situation: drafting an ending and looking for ways to tighten its felt connection to the story's earlier signal moments
    - outcome: → folded into parameter-table-for-recurrence (the structural rhyme is one row in the parameter schema — "ominous late-night gate event" — that recurs and varies across the story; the underlying procedure is the same controlled-variation tracking the new skill operationalizes; treating it as a separate skill would create a near-duplicate at lower specificity)

- Chapter 9: A Pattern Story
    - location: line 2663 ("if they find themselves trapped in exposition, writing pages and pages in which their action doesn't rise, all they need to do is drop this sentence into their story: 'Then something happened that changed everything forever.' The story has no choice but to respond.")
    - paraphrase: the joke teaching device: when stuck in exposition, force a story-level event by inserting a sentence that promises rising action
    - situation: a writer paralyzed in exposition
    - outcome: → dropped because Saunders explicitly frames this as a joke ("I sometimes joke with my students"); it has no observable signal beyond the joke itself, and the genuine procedural move it gestures toward is captured by refuse-to-repeat-beats (locate where you have stopped escalating and find the next nudge)

- Chapter 9: A Pattern Story
    - location: lines 2906-2918 (the football-field-choreography analogy; the neutralized "9 on a scale of 10" version that lacks internal dynamics; "the difference between a master halftime-show choreographer and a hack is the attention paid to the details of internal dynamics")
    - paraphrase: a story means through internal dynamics — the patterned, felt juxtaposition of one part with another — not just through plot summary; flat-leveled summary statements destroy meaning by removing the variation that lets things like "progress" and "tragedy" be inferred
    - situation: a writer or critic flattening a story into a plot summary and losing the meaning that lived in the variation between parts
    - outcome: → folded into parameter-table-for-recurrence (this is the motivating image for the parameter-tracking procedure: the "internal dynamics" that the choreography analogy points at ARE what the parameter table makes visible; treating the analogy as a separate skill would not add a procedural move)

- Chapter 9: A Pattern Story
    - location: lines 3120-3132, 3162-3172 (Chekhov "sets some feature of the world in the middle of a room and invites us to walk around it, looking at it from different angles"; the "is this trait good or bad?" question and Chekhov's answer "Yes"; the closing meditation that infinite information would, like God's, switch on "some essential mercy")
    - paraphrase: a stance toward character in which the writer presents the same trait from contradictory angles without resolving it, allowing the reader to know the character "in all kinds of weather" rather than to judge them
    - situation: writing a character whose central trait the reader will be tempted to judge
    - outcome: → dropped because the action ("present from different angles") is too vague to produce an observable signal; the underlying procedural moves Saunders uses to achieve this — increasing-specification at the level of contradictory traits, holding-up-against-the-heart for ironic juxtaposition, refuse-to-repeat-beats for forcing each angle to add new information — are already covered; what remains is the parent-context disposition (resistance literature, every human worthy of attention) already in _book.md

- Chapter 10: Afterthought #3
    - location: lines 3197-3209 (the index-cards-on-a-date image; "if we set out to do a thing, and then we (merely) do it, everyone is bummed out"; story must outgrow its early understanding of itself; Donald Barthelme on the writer who "does not know what to do"; Gerald Stern on the two-dogs-fucking poem; Einstein paraphrase on no problem solved in the plane of its original conception)
    - paraphrase: refuse to merely execute the plan you brought into the writing session; respond to the moment-to-moment energy of the work instead, allowing the story to outgrow its early understanding of itself
    - situation: a writer who has arrived at the page with a settled intention (an outline, a thesis, a planned scene) and is about to execute it without responsiveness
    - outcome: → folded into iterative-preference-revision (this is the disposition the iterative method already operationalizes: revise by reaction, not by execution; the index-cards image is a fresh metaphor for the same anti-top-down stance the existing skill names. Adds to the failure-mode framing: the "plan-as-data-dump-or-lecture" outcome is what the iterative method refuses)

- Chapter 10: Afterthought #3
    - location: lines 3219-3223 (Hot Wheels gas-stations metaphor; "every sentence is a potential little gas station"; manifestations of writerly charm; the writer figures out across thousands of hours which gas stations she is uniquely capable of making)
    - paraphrase: read every sentence as a potential propulsion unit for the reader; identify your own unique writerly charms (humor, honesty, rhythm, pithy description) and cultivate them as a set of impulses you habitually honor, rather than imitating someone else's charms
    - situation: a writer building a sustainable line-level practice and trying to figure out what kinds of sentences propel HER specific reader through HER prose
    - outcome: → dropped because the action ("identify your unique writerly charms") has no observable signal at session scope; Saunders explicitly frames it as a discovery occurring across "thousands of hours of work" with no procedural form short of that; what is procedurally testable here is mode-level (covered by energy-not-aspiration) and sentence-level reaction-tracking (covered by iterative-preference-revision); the "gas station" image is a vivid restatement of the same propulsion criterion both skills already operationalize. The metaphor adds no new procedural content the existing skills do not already supply

- Chapter 10: Afterthought #3
    - location: lines 3225-3239 (the most urgent question "What makes MY reader keep reading?"; the "weird assumption" that our reader reads the way we do; the movie-theater audience gasping in unison; the core skill of impersonating yourself reading your own prose for the first time; manifesting to the reader as evidence of care; the first-time reader can intuit "the many less-cared-for versions of a sentence behind the one the writer let stand")
    - paraphrase: the central revision skill is to read your own prose as if it were entirely new to you, monitoring your responses and changing accordingly; the reader registers this work as evidence of care, intuiting the discarded alternatives behind every kept choice
    - situation: any revision pass over your own draft
    - outcome: → folded into iterative-preference-revision (this is exactly the procedure the existing skill names: "Read it from the top, trying to read as a first-time reader would." Ch 10 sharpens the framing in two ways worth folding in: the goal is not to imagine some ideal external reader but to "lapse into a reasonable impersonation of yourself reading as if the prose was entirely new to you," and the reader-side effect of doing this is "evidence of care" — an intuited sense of the less-cared-for versions behind the kept one. Both refinements deepen the existing skill's failure-mode framing without producing a separate procedure)

- Chapter 10: Afterthought #3
    - location: lines 3241-3245 (revision as practicing relationship; running the meter over phrases, sentences, sections; "the difference between a sentence that is pleasing... and one that displeases her... I find I can't complete that sentence, not in any general way. And I don't need to. To be a writer, I only need to read a specific sentence of mine, in its particular context, on a given day, pencil in hand, changing the sentence as it occurs to me to do so")
    - paraphrase: refuse to ask what makes a good sentence in the abstract; ask only of this specific sentence in this specific context, with pencil in hand, then do that again
    - situation: a writer or critic seeking a general theory of good prose before working on the actual prose
    - outcome: → folded into iterative-preference-revision (the existing skill's "do not pre-plan the meaning" rule already refuses general theory; the chapter's locality framing — "specific sentence, particular context, given day, pencil in hand" — is the same anti-abstraction stance restated, and is worth absorbing into the skill's failure-mode wording as a sharpening of why the iterative method is not a fallback but the entire shape of the work)

- Chapter 10: Afterthought #3
    - location: lines 3239 ("when we're reading along and something deflects our needle into the N zone, this tells us that, in the instant of the writing, we weren't there. (When I write, 'The orange sunset was a beautiful orange color,' this indicates that, at the time of the writing, I wasn't there.)")
    - paraphrase: when revising and the needle drops to N, diagnose it as a moment when the writer was not present (was on autopilot, executing rather than perceiving); use revision as the chance to "be there" attentively
    - situation: a revision pass where N-drops are accumulating
    - outcome: → folded into iterative-preference-revision (this names the diagnostic content of an N-drop: a place where the writer was absent at the time of writing. The existing skill already operationalizes the response — make the small fix that comes to mind — and the "presence" framing is the same disposition the P/N meter trains; Ch 10 supplies the second-order diagnosis ("not there at the time of writing") as a reframe of the failure mode, not a new procedure)

- Chapter 11: Master and Man (Tolstoy source story)
    - location: lines 3251-4172 (entire chapter)
    - paraphrase: no candidates. The chapter is Tolstoy's story as Saunders presents it, with no Saunders commentary. Visible structural features include the patterned departures-and-arrivals across the snowstorm (initial departure from Kresty, lost on the Zakharov field, recovery in Grishkino, second departure with Petrushka as guide, lost again at the ravine, unharness and stop for the night, Vasili's solo flight on Mukhorty), the literal sledge-circling in which Vasili rides in a circle and finds his own hoofprints, the long accumulation of factual descriptive detail (Nikita harnessing Mukhorty, the samovar at Taras's, the household talk of separation) before the freezing scene, the structural rhyme between Vasili's two cigarette-lightings and the framed contrast between Vasili's interior money-counting and Nikita's acceptance of the Chief Master, the master's final reversal in covering Nikita with his body, and the narrator's epilogue jump-forward that shows Nikita living another twenty years and the closing first-person plural "we shall all soon learn." Each is a teachable feature in principle, but the procedural form (action, observable signal, named failure mode) cannot be articulated honestly from the story alone without anticipating Chapter 12's commentary ("And Yet They Drove On"), which is out of scope for this pass.
    - situation: not applicable
    - outcome: → none promoted; the story is data the next chapter will use to teach moves about Tolstoy's matrix of facts, the suprapersonal wisdom of the novel, and the structural shaping that delivers the master's reversal

- Chapter 12: And Yet They Drove On (Thoughts on "Master and Man")
    - location: lines 4181-4213 (Tolstoy's prose is "almost entirely facts"; the samovar-flick passage embroiders an action with concrete factual details rather than authorial commentary; even subjective judgments and characters' thoughts are rendered "succinctly and precisely, using simple objective sentences that seem factual in their syntax and modesty of assertion"; "a fact draws us in"; the dented red car parking-lot example; subjective claims arrive in a matrix of facts and are accepted in the same spirit as the bridle being leather and tasseled)
    - paraphrase: write at a register where every sentence reads as a concrete factual report — actions, objects, named gestures — and put even subjective claims (a character is cheerful, a host is honestly convinced) into that same factual syntax so the reader accepts them by the same acceptance reflex that swallows the fact-statements around them
    - situation: drafting prose in which the writer wants the reader to accept characterization, judgment, or interior states without being asked to take the writer's word for it; or revising prose whose elevated, poetic, or aphoristic register is producing skepticism rather than belief
    - outcome: → promoted to matrix-of-facts
- Chapter 12: And Yet They Drove On
    - location: lines 4253-4293 (the five-shifts-of-vantage-point passage on Vasili and Nikita: omniscient narrator declares the objective truth that Vasili cheats Nikita; Vasili speaks the lie in dialogue; Vasili thinks, revealing he's "honestly convinced" he's a benefactor; Nikita responds in dialogue with his own spin; Nikita's thoughts confirm he knows he's being cheated. Then the second worked instance, the Grishkino departure, with five vantage points across four paragraphs ending in "no one to hinder the departing travelers"; "what makes us think of Tolstoy as a moral-ethical giant here is a technique (going from mind to mind) coupled with a confidence... that he has an inner Vasili, an inner aged host, an inner Petrushka, an inner Nikita")
    - paraphrase: rotate vantage among objective narration, public speech, and private thought across each character involved in a morally loaded exchange, so the reader can see the gap between what each says and what each privately knows; the technique requires the writer's confidence that they have an inner version of every character on the page
    - situation: drafting or revising a scene whose center is a moral exchange (a hypocrisy, a transaction with mixed motives, a lie passed in conversation) and the prose currently shows only one of public-speech / private-thought / objective-narration, leaving the reader unable to feel where each character stands relative to the truth
    - outcome: → promoted to mind-to-mind-vantage-shifts
- Chapter 12: And Yet They Drove On
    - location: lines 4309-4346 (the mansion-tour analogy: announcing "we're working our way down" buys digression-tolerance; "We're driving out to buy that land" as the announced organizing principle of "Master and Man"; the section-by-section outline showing the four cycles of getting-lost and coming-home)
    - paraphrase: announce the trip / quest / structural plan early so digressions later in the piece are read against the announced through-line and don't disorient the reader
    - situation: drafting a long-form work whose middle digressions feel pointless to early readers
    - outcome: → folded into hollywood-version (the announced organizing principle is the same one-sentence shape the Hollywood version names; what the existing skill operationalizes for the writer's planning, this passage extends to the reader's experience: state it inside the story so the reader can hold it. The procedural action is the same — produce the one-sentence shape — and treating the reader-side announcement as a separate skill would not add a new procedure)
- Chapter 12: And Yet They Drove On
    - location: lines 4346-4378 (the embedded "shadow structure": each of the ten sections begins with a desire/problem/setback and ends with the dangled hope of some improvement; the tightrope-walker uptick analogy; "we're being swept downriver by the strong current of the overall organizing principle, while being caught along the way in a series of small, distracting local eddies")
    - paraphrase: install a small setback-and-relief or problem-and-dangled-hope motion inside each major structural unit so that each section delivers its own miniature recovery, providing local propulsion that masks the overall arc
    - situation: drafting or revising a long-form piece whose overall trajectory is relentlessly downward (or upward) and individual sections feel exhausting because they offer no local pulses of recovery
    - outcome: → folded into parameter-table-for-recurrence (the shadow structure IS a parameter that recurs across all ten sections — "section begins with: ___; section ends with: ___" — and its meaning is generated by reading down the column. The new fold note: this chapter sharpens the procedure by showing the parameter-table can encode mini-arcs as parameters, not just elements; what changes from row to row can be the shape of the unit itself)
- Chapter 12: And Yet They Drove On
    - location: lines 4395-4426 (the "lesser writer" version of the lost-on-the-road sequence vs. Tolstoy's: random sequence of events vs. each beat caused by the prior; Saunders names "increased causality" as the difference; "two things separate writers who go on to publish... the extent to which the writer has learned to make causality"; the Forster king-and-queen formulation; "causality is to the writer what melody is to the songwriter"; the painted-kite-and-wind metaphor; lines 4435-4451 walking the sled-of-drunken-peasants race through the explicit causal chain — the race fires Vasili up, his elation causes him to drive boldly without watching way-marks, that causes them to get lost again)
    - paraphrase: when revising a sequence where one beat follows another, do not accept "and then" as the connector; ask of each beat what about the prior beat caused it, and rewrite until the causal chain is explicit; treat causality as the load-bearing variable that converts a sequence of events into a story with apparent meaning
    - situation: drafting or revising a sequence in which things happen but reads as episodic; reader cannot say why each event followed the one before; sentences are individually fine but the chain feels arbitrary
    - outcome: → promoted to causality-not-sequence
- Chapter 12: And Yet They Drove On
    - location: lines 4461-4488 (the four-times-passing clothesline outside Grishkino: first time fluttering wildly with the white shirt struggling, second time the white shirt attached only by one frozen sleeve, third time still fluttering desperately, fourth time the linen "no longer to be seen"; "each time we pass that clothesline, the laundry has undergone some small change in its condition. We read this as an escalation, or at least a mini-escalation — a 'refusal to repeat'"; the place-setting/silverware-tracking-shot example: four arrangements with progressive subtractions reads as "evacuation" or "diminishment"; "always be escalating' can be understood as 'be alert, always, to the possibilities you have created for variation'")
    - paraphrase: when an element recurs, vary one or more parameters across the recurrences so the column read-down generates inferred meaning (escalation, decline, evacuation), rather than letting the recurrence sit as a static repeat
    - situation: drafting a story with a recurring detail (a clothesline, a dish, a place setting, a sound) and the second appearance is about to be a copy of the first
    - outcome: → folded into parameter-table-for-recurrence (Saunders himself cross-references the Olenka chapter — "earlier, we defined escalation as that which results when we refuse to repeat beats" — and the procedure is identical: tabulate the repeated element, vary the parameters, read down the column to surface meaning. This is a fresh worked instance of parameter-table-for-recurrence at the level of a recurring physical detail rather than a relationship; fold note adds the place-setting analogy as an even more compressed worked example)
- Chapter 12: And Yet They Drove On
    - location: lines 4495-4525 (the Grishkino-stop section as a structural unit "shaped like Freytag's triangle"; the conversation about "young people getting out of hand" as the unit's climactic moment; "if a structural unit in a story we're writing isn't shaped like that, we might wonder if it wants to be; if it is shaped like that, we might want to make that shape sharper")
    - paraphrase: every structural unit (a scene, a stop along a journey, a chapter, an interlude) wants its own miniature rising-action-and-climax shape; locate the unit's exposition / rising action / climactic moment, and sharpen the shape if it's there or add it if it isn't
    - situation: drafting or critiquing a structural unit that feels dilated and expositional with no internal pulse
    - outcome: → folded into cornfeld-principle (the existing skill already tests every structural unit against entertainment + non-trivial advancement; this chapter's contribution is a sharper procedural form for the second criterion: the unit advances the story partly by enacting its own miniature arc. The fold note adds Freytag's-triangle-per-unit as the shape the second Cornfeld criterion implicitly demands; treating it as a separate skill would create a near-duplicate that fires whenever the existing skill fires)
- Chapter 12: And Yet They Drove On
    - location: lines 4549-4567 (the structural-core-of-Section-VI passage: Vasili's coping methods (cigarettes, disparaging others, bragging to himself, running the numbers, victorious thinking) work the first time around and then fail in the same sequence the second time; "the structural core of this section is a simple before-and-after pattern. Which offers us lesser writers a technique: if we want change to appear to happen in our stories, the first order of business is to note specifically how things are now"; the dusty-table / newly-dusted-table example as the smallest possible instance of the move)
    - paraphrase: to make change visible without narrating it, first specify how things are now in concrete observable terms (the table is dusty), then later, in the same idiom, show how things are different (the newly dusted table gleams); the change is inferred by the reader because the parameters that were specified before are observably altered after, and the change of an entity's state implies an actor who changed it
    - situation: drafting or revising a section in which a character has changed and the writer is tempted to narrate the change directly; the section feels like telling, not showing
    - outcome: → folded into parameter-table-for-recurrence (this is parameter-tracking applied to a single entity across two passes through the same parameters — "Vasili's coping methods" as a parameter table with two rows: works/fails. The procedure is the same controlled-variation read-down. The fold note adds: when the parameter-table has only two rows and the parameters fail uniformly in the second, the read-down is "this person has changed.")
- Chapter 12: And Yet They Drove On
    - location: lines 4663-4709, 4731-4737 (Tolstoy's transformation of Vasili: "Vasili does not launch into a soliloquy or internal monologue describing his changed feelings... he doesn't announce that he has 'realized' something. The order of operations is not: a change overcomes him, and then he realizes this, tells us about it, then acts. He just acts (or, actually, goes back into action). And he goes back into action just like himself"; the "same resolution with which he used to strike hands when making a good purchase"; lines 4731-4737: "moral transformation, when it happens, happens not through the total remaking of the sinner or the replacement of his habitual energy with some pure new energy but by a redirection of his (same old) energy"; the worried-vs-activist example, the bull-and-china-shop redirection; the post-transformation Vasili remaining "still self-celebratory, still living to feel good about himself"; lines 4583-4585 the "lesser writer" version: "have the bad person do some thinking, and come to a revelation, and start acting resolutely on that thought")
    - paraphrase: when a character has to change in a story, refuse to write the soliloquy of realization; instead, render the changed character acting in their familiar manner with their familiar energy redirected at a new object, and let the reader infer the change from the action rather than from any announcement of it; preserve the character's selfish or boastful or anxious voice, post-change, so the change reads as redirection rather than replacement
    - situation: drafting a scene in which a character is supposed to change (a stinker becomes generous, a coward acts bravely, a skeptic comes to believe), and the obvious move is to give them a moment of realization, an internal monologue announcing the change, and a clean break from their old self
    - outcome: → promoted to transformation-by-redirected-energy

- Chapter 13: Afterthought #4
    - location: lines 4796-4805 (the Gogol "Nevsky Prospect" classroom episode: a student says the story is sexist, Saunders asks "Where?", the student locates two passages where a man's insult provokes interior monologue and a woman's insult provokes a narrator joke at her expense; the class then imagines the corrected story with internal monologue equally distributed; Saunders generalizes the principle: "any story that suffers from what seems like a moral failing (that seems sexist, racist, homophobic, transphobic, pedantic, appropriative, derivative of another writer's work, and so on) will be seen, with sufficient analytical snooping, to be suffering from a technical failing, and if that failing is addressed, it will (always) become a better story"); lines 4804 (worked instance on "Master and Man": "Tolstoy seems to be exhibiting class bias" gets converted to the technical observation "In (at least) two places, when Nikita comes home from the hospital and in their respective death scenes, Nikita is denied the interiority that Tolstoy gave Vasili in similar moments"); lines 4754-4784 (the worked diagnosis itself: Section VII gives Nikita a "less interesting, less detailed" interior pass than Section VI gives Vasili; Section X gives Nikita's twenty later years and his death without the interiority granted Vasili at the parallel moment of his own death in Section IX; the downstream consequence is that Nikita never thinks of Vasili, never reflects on the sacrifice, walks off unchanged, "which is...strange. If a person gives his life to save another person, and the saved person never thinks about it, doesn't appear grateful, seems unchanged by it, it makes us wonder about the value of the sacrifice. It also makes us wonder about the person saved. It also makes us wonder about the writer."); lines 4810-4820 (the corrective exercise: imagine the version of Section X in which Nikita is granted narrative resources equal to Vasili's at parallel moments; what does Nikita think of Vasili now, is he astonished or confused, how does he process the fact that Vasili sacrificed his life for him; rework the closing paragraph to be as omniscient as Vasili's death; "rewrite Section X. Write it like Tolstoy. Use, you know, a lot of facts.")
    - paraphrase: when a story is criticized for a moral failing (sexism, racism, class bias, etc.), refuse to either accept the moral verdict as final or dismiss it; ask "Where, exactly?", get the citations, and convert each into a neutral technical observation about an inequity in how the prose treats characters at parallel moments (interior monologue granted to one and denied to another, omniscient access provided here and withheld there, narrator's jokes weighted at one party's expense, deferred-time epilogue rendered with full lens for one and bare facts for the other); the converted form names a fix the writer can apply
    - situation: a critic, student, workshop, or your own reading raises a moral concern about a story (it seems sexist / racist / classist / pedantic / appropriative); or you are reading a story that is "wonderful" but you sense a moral asymmetry you cannot articulate; or you are revising a draft and someone has flagged a bias you do not think you intended; the moral framing is general, sticky, and unactionable as stated
    - outcome: → promoted to convert-moral-critique-to-technical

- Chapter 13: Afterthought #4
    - location: lines 4794-4814 (the parallel-moments audit: Vasili gets a long inner monologue closing Section IX as he dies; Nikita gets bare facts of his own death in Section X plus the deferral "we'll have to wait for our own deaths to see whether Nikita was disappointed or found there what he expected"; the corrective exercise is staged as: "a version of Section X in which Nikita is granted narrative resources equal to the ones Tolstoy granted Vasili at parallel moments")
    - paraphrase: identify two characters who occupy parallel structural positions in a story (both die, both come home from a journey, both face the same test) and audit whether each was granted the same narrative resources at their parallel moment — interior monologue, omniscient access, time on the page, the writer's full investment in their inner life
    - situation: revising or critiquing a story whose two principal characters occupy parallel positions and you suspect the prose treats them unequally without having decided to
    - outcome: → folded into convert-moral-critique-to-technical (the parallel-moments audit IS the operationalization of the conversion when the moral concern is character bias; treating it as a separate skill would create a near-duplicate that fires whenever the conversion fires for bias-shaped accusations. The new skill names the parallel-moments check as its core procedure)

- Chapter 13: Afterthought #4
    - location: lines 4768-4784 (the twenty-years-later test: after a sacrifice, the saved party is followed forward and we ask whether the change shows; "we never see Nikita wondering about that crazy night at the sled. He doesn't reflect on Vasili's cowardice or his redemption, never asks 'Why did my master do that?' or 'What happened to him, there at the end?' Vasili felt that he and Nikita had merged into one person, but Nikita? Not so much. He doesn't seem grateful to Vasili. He doesn't think of Vasili at all"; the consequence: "if a person gives his life to save another person, and the saved person never thinks about it, doesn't appear grateful, seems unchanged by it, it makes us wonder about the value of the sacrifice. It also makes us wonder about the person saved. It also makes us wonder about the writer.")
    - paraphrase: when a story stages a sacrifice or transformative event, follow the person on the receiving end forward in time and check whether their later actions, thoughts, or words register the event; if they do not, the sacrifice's stakes, the recipient's interiority, and the writer's seriousness all become questionable
    - situation: drafting or critiquing a story with a sacrifice / transformation / pivotal gift whose receiving party is followed past the event into later sections
    - outcome: → folded into convert-moral-critique-to-technical (this is the chapter's worked diagnosis used to motivate the conversion: the unchanged-savee is itself a manifestation of denied-interiority; Saunders writes "It also makes us wonder about the writer" to land the technical-not-moral framing. The procedure that surfaces the problem — does the recipient reflect on the event later, in a way commensurate with what the giver experienced — is the parallel-moments audit, already absorbed into the new skill. Treating the unchanged-savee as a separate skill would fragment the chapter's single new teaching)

- Chapter 13: Afterthought #4
    - location: lines 4810-4820 (the corrective exercise on Section X: imagine and write the version where Nikita is granted equal narrative resources; "rewrite Section X. Write it like Tolstoy. Use, you know, a lot of facts.")
    - paraphrase: once a technical inequity has been named, write the corrected version (the rebalanced scene, the granted interior monologue, the omniscient death) and read it against the original to confirm the fix; the rewrite is the test that the conversion was useful
    - situation: any case where you have converted a moral critique to a technical observation and want to verify the fix
    - outcome: → folded into two-version-comparison (this is the existing two-version-comparison move applied to the corrected version of an inequitable passage rather than to a craft choice whose effect you cannot articulate; the procedure is the same, write the inverted/corrected version and hold the two side by side. The new skill convert-moral-critique-to-technical references this fold for the verification step)

- Chapter 14: The Nose (Gogol source story)
    - location: lines 4833-5167 (entire chapter)
    - paraphrase: no candidates. The chapter is Gogol's story as Saunders presents it, with no Saunders commentary. Visible features include the absurdist register in which the disappeared nose is treated as an ordinary fact requiring bureaucratic redress, the inflated ranks-and-titles vocabulary (Collegiate Assessor, state councillor, field officer's wife) invoked at every social moment, the Nose's appearance as an autonomous person of higher rank than its owner (Kazan Cathedral scene), the narrator's two explicit refusals to explain the chain of events ("the whole episode becomes shrouded in mist", "the whole incident is shrouded in fog"), the inserted exchange of letters between Kovalyov and Mrs. Podtochina, the comic mismatch between the metaphysical strangeness of the disappearance and the petty social calculations it provokes (whom Kovalyov can no longer call on, the marriage prospects, the visit to the newspaper office), and the closing self-interrogation in which the narrator audibly admits the story makes no sense and yet ends "such things happen in this world; rarely, but they do." Each is a teachable feature in principle, but the procedural form (action, observable signal, named failure mode) cannot be articulated honestly from the story alone without anticipating Chapter 15's commentary, which is out of scope for this pass.
    - situation: not applicable
    - outcome: → none promoted; the story is data the next chapter will use to teach moves about absurdist register, treating the strange as fact, the bureaucratic hierarchy as a comic engine, the structural use of unexplained gaps, and the narrator's closing confession.

- Chapter 15: The Door to the Truth Might Be Strangeness (Thoughts on "The Nose")
    - location: lines 5197-5220 (the wheelbarrow-of-things assignment and the introduction of the nose-in-bread; "If a writer introduces a strange event, then lets the fictive world respond to that event, what we're really learning about is what we might call the fictive world's psychological physics. What are the rules there? How do things proceed? A story like that will feel truthful and essential to the extent that the psychological physics of the fictive world are felt to be similar to the psychological physics of our own"; "we wait to see how the fictive world will react to it. That's where the story's meaning is going to be made, not in the fact of the nose in the bread but in what the couple does about it in response. This world... is not our world, but it is a world, and there are going to be rules in that world, and we wait to see what they are")
    - paraphrase: when a story declines consensus reality (impossible event, talking objects, surreal premise), the meaning is made not by the strangeness but by the rules the fictive world reveals as it responds; locate the meaning at the response, calibrate the response so its psychological physics resemble our own, and accustom the reader to the world's rules step by step so each later strangeness lands inside an established system. Includes the limit-stretching observation (5494-5495) — by the newspaper-office scene we're "now arguing earnestly for the ad to be run, having accepted not only the reality of a nose's conversion into a person but the idea that a notice in a newspaper might help us find it"; the polite-mild reactions (5470-5474) — bystanders react to the impossible with strangely mild civility, that mildness IS the meaning-making engine; and the shards-not-vase (5560) — the long-form effect of stacked tiers is that the story reads as coherent on the first pass even though "the pieces don't fit, because it was never a coherent vase to begin with"
    - situation: drafting or revising a story whose premise involves an impossible event, a surreal element, an object treated as a person, or any departure from consensus reality, and you are unsure how to make the strangeness mean rather than merely happen
    - outcome: → promoted to psychological-physics-of-strangeness

- Chapter 15: The Door to the Truth Might Be Strangeness (Thoughts on "The Nose")
    - location: lines 5252-5263 (the explicit naming: "This scene, like the entire story, is infused with what we might call Multiple Superimposed Weirdness Syndrome. Initial weirdness: a nose appears in a loaf of bread. Second-level weirdness: the couple reacts irrationally to the nose's presence in the bread. Third-level weirdness: because they've reacted irrationally, they make an odd plan in response (ditch the nose). Fourth-level weirdness: Ivan executes the plan badly... And there's one more level of weirdness, one that has to do with how the story's being told")
    - paraphrase: when stacking strangeness across tiers (premise, character reaction, plan, execution, narration), each new tier should add weirdness in a different category from the prior tier rather than restate the prior tier in louder form; the procedure for a draft that plateaus on its surreal premise is to enumerate the existing tiers, identify which categories have not yet been weird-ified, and ratchet the strangeness up one notch in a fresh category
    - situation: drafting or revising a story whose initial strangeness was strong but whose middle pages feel like they are restating the strangeness rather than compounding it; the draft is sitting at one tier of weirdness when it could be at four
    - outcome: → promoted to multiple-superimposed-weirdness

- Chapter 15: The Door to the Truth Might Be Strangeness (Thoughts on "The Nose")
    - location: lines 5274-5289 (the named technique: "The narration in 'The Nose,' it turns out, is a particular Russian form of unreliable first-person narration called skaz... He's pedantic and superior and overestimates his intelligence and charm... He's decidedly not Gogol but a creation of Gogol's, another character in the story, a functionary who, through his prose style, unconsciously reveals that he's not as important or smart as he thinks he is"; "this isn't graceless writing; this is a great writer writing a graceless writer writing"); also lines 5300-5328 (the two-cartoon-bubbles model of communication, which Saunders names as the everyday version of skaz)
    - paraphrase: when narration would otherwise be neutrally omniscient, treat the narrator as a character with limitations whose voice (digressions that prove the wrong thing, misplaced emphasis, failures to register the strangeness around him, pedantic literary aspiration that misfires) is itself revealing; the procedure is to write the graceless narrator deliberately, while the actual writer remains in control above; signals include misfired digressions, syntax that overestimates its own elegance, and a non-registering reaction to the loaded events being narrated
    - situation: drafting or revising a story where the narrative voice currently functions as an invisible camera, or where the meaning of the story includes what the narrator does not see; you want the narrator's failures (not just the characters') to be a load-bearing surface
    - outcome: → promoted to skaz-narrator

- Chapter 15: The Door to the Truth Might Be Strangeness (Thoughts on "The Nose")
    - location: lines 5300-5328 (Doug Unger's two-cartoon-bubbles model: "When two people are talking, Doug suggested, each has a cartoon bubble overhead, full of his or her private hopes and projections and fears and preexisting worries and so on. Person A talks, Person B listens, waiting to respond, but as what Person A is saying passes into Person B's cartoon bubble, it gets mangled"; the mother-birthday / speech-anxiety worked example)
    - paraphrase: before composing a dialogue scene whose meaning depends on miscommunication, prepopulate each character's interior bubble with private content unrelated to the other's, then write the dialogue so each speaker's words pass through the other's bubble and arrive distorted; the distortion is the meaning
    - situation: drafting a dialogue exchange where the meaning depends on what each character privately brings to the conversation rather than on the overt content of the exchange itself
    - outcome: → folded into mind-to-mind-vantage-shifts (the existing skill rotates among public-speech, private-thought, and objective-narration during morally loaded exchanges; this chapter sharpens the procedure for the case where the two characters' private contents are unrelated to each other and to the surface conversation, with the bubble-preload as the preparatory step. Treating it as a separate skill would create a near-duplicate that fires whenever mind-to-mind fires for a miscommunication-shaped scene)

- Chapter 15: The Door to the Truth Might Be Strangeness (Thoughts on "The Nose")
    - location: lines 5346-5367 (improper narrative emphasis at the moment Kovalyov first sees his Nose: "Imagine the horror and at the same time the amazement of Kovalyov when he recognized that it was his own nose!"; "What's the 'it'? Who's the 'him'? What, exactly, does Kovalyov see? Does the Nose have... a nose? Does the Nose have a face? If so, its face is not described. But the confident statement that 'he recognized that it was his own nose' causes our mind to insert, here, a Platonic Nose, one that we couldn't, if pressed, draw"; "This is 'improper narrative emphasis' being used to sidestep a question that, had these events really happened, and had we been there, we would have been able to answer"; "The focus is on the nose's change in status, not its new form or size")
    - paraphrase: when the literal mechanics of an impossible event would, if rendered, expose its nonsense, deflect by emphasizing a different attribute (rank, costume, social status, mood) so the reader's mind supplies a Platonic version of the unrenderable thing; the test is whether you can name the question you are sidestepping ("does the Nose have a face?") and whether the deflection sits inside a confident syntactic frame
    - situation: drafting a scene with an impossible or unrenderable element where direct description would force a choice between two incompatible specifications, or would break the spell by making the impossibility too literal
    - outcome: → promoted to improper-narrative-emphasis

- Chapter 15: The Door to the Truth Might Be Strangeness (Thoughts on "The Nose")
    - location: lines 5648-5678 (the narrator's closing confession: "'Only now, on second thoughts,' the narrator says, 'can we see that there is much that is improbable in it'"; "The car dealer, in mid-transaction, wonders aloud how he can stand here telling me all of these lies, and I respond to his honesty with a renewed burst of trust and end up buying the car"; "He addresses exactly none of the concerns he's raised... but the flailing gestures he's making in that direction have the effect of emptying out my TICHN cart"; "I make a protest about the story's failure to cohere logically. 'I know, right?' the narrator says. 'It's a train wreck, isn't it?' Somehow that's enough"); also the bus-driver and dinner-party analogies (5662-5666)
    - paraphrase: when a story has accumulated unaddressed strangeness (loose ends, implausibilities, narrator-quirks the reader has been silently tracking), the ending move is for the narrator (or the prose) to confess the oddness rather than resolve it; the confession does not need to answer any of the raised questions, only to acknowledge them; the signal is that the reader's residual suspicion drops away even though the irregularities remain unresolved
    - situation: revising a story whose surface has piled up implausibilities that the reader has been patiently tracking, and where any explanation you might write would dissipate the strangeness that gave the story its truth-value; you sense the ending needs to address the cart of suspicions but cannot resolve them without ruining the effect
    - outcome: → promoted to confess-the-oddness

- Chapter 15: The Door to the Truth Might Be Strangeness (Thoughts on "The Nose")
    - location: lines 5390-5402 (the two models of writing: "One model of writing is that we strive upward to express ourselves precisely, at the highest levels of language (think Henry James). Another is that we surrender to our natural mode of expression, flawed though it may be, and, by way of concentrated work within that mode, raise it up, so to speak, creating a poetic rarefication of that (inefficient) form of expression"); the corporate-poem worked example showing a "not right" speech that "is a poem, because it is not right. There's a true statement inside it ('We failed and are fucked'), but there's also something true about its not-rightness, the flavor of which tells us things about the speaker and his culture that aren't conveyed by 'We failed and are fucked'"
    - paraphrase: when your natural mode of expression is awkward, vernacular, or "wrong" relative to your aspired upward-striving model, surrender to it and refine it within its own grain rather than trying to climb out of it; "every soul is vast and wants to express itself fully... if it's denied an adequate instrument, out comes... poetry, i.e., truth forced out through a restricted opening"
    - situation: a writer who can articulate what they aspire to sound like (literary, elevated, James-ian, Hemingway-ian) is producing prose that sounds like a worse version of the aspired voice, while their natural off-license register would, if surrendered to and refined, generate a distinctive thing
    - outcome: → folded into energy-not-aspiration (the existing skill names the choice as energy-vs-aspiration; this chapter adds the second-half framing — once you have abandoned the aspirational mode, the work is to refine the natural mode within its own grain rather than to re-stretch toward the original aspiration. The "throw yourself at the fence of language" / "concentrated work within the natural mode" framing is added as the post-abandonment procedure)

- Chapter 15: The Door to the Truth Might Be Strangeness (Thoughts on "The Nose")
    - location: lines 5610-5621 (the unchanged Kovalyov: "What change does its main character undergo? How do the events of the story 'change everything forever'?... Kovalyov's nose leaves him, then comes back. It refuses to reattach and then, seemingly on a whim, reattaches. What does Kovalyov learn from this terrible trial? Nothing"; the medical-test analogy at 5620 — "Could this be it? Our life suddenly seems precious, our habits stupid... The results come back: all is well. The mind relaxes into its previous torpor")
    - paraphrase: a valid story shape ends with the protagonist returning to their pre-event self, having registered nothing; the action is to recognize this as a deliberate option rather than a failure of the writer to deliver transformation, and to design the ending so the lack-of-change is itself the meaning
    - situation: drafting a story whose protagonist undergoes an ordeal but whose nature is not such that they would learn from it; you feel pressure to deliver a transformation arc and suspect doing so would betray the character
    - outcome: → folded into transformation-by-redirected-energy (the existing skill addresses how to write a moral transformation when one is happening; this chapter adds the explicit contrast condition — when the character is constituted such that they will not change, the right move is the unchanged-protagonist ending; the medical-test analogy is added as the worked instance of the contrast. Treating this as a separate skill would create a contrasts-pair without a distinct procedure beyond "consider whether the character must change")

- Chapter 15: The Door to the Truth Might Be Strangeness (Thoughts on "The Nose")
    - location: lines 5598-5601 (the joy-burst: "But we'd be remiss if we didn't acknowledge that Gogol's main currency is joy. My favorite part of the story... comes toward the beginning of the scene in the newspaper office when somehow, magically, a group of people waiting to place ads get transformed into that for which they are advertising, and suddenly that little office is full of 'a coachman of sober conduct... a nineteen-year-old serf girl... a sound droshky with one spring missing... a young and fiery dappled-gray horse... a summer residence with all the appurtenances'"; "That is what makes Gogol great, that he somehow felt inclined to do that, and then did it, with such strange, happy confidence. The inexplicable uptick in fondness for the world I feel, moving through that section, which is not essential to the action of the story but seems to have been done just for the fun of it, is, for me, what Gogol is all about")
    - paraphrase: a passage that fails the Cornfeld test (does not advance the story or tell us about a character in a non-trivial way) but produces a marked uptick of fondness or delight in the reader is its own warrant for inclusion; joy-burst is a recognized exception to the "every scene must earn its place" rule
    - situation: revising and applying the Cornfeld principle to a passage that flagrantly fails both criteria but nevertheless feels like the soul of the piece; you suspect cutting it would prune the writer's best instinct
    - outcome: → folded into cornfeld-principle (the existing skill names two criteria the scene must meet to earn its place; this chapter adds an explicit exception condition — a passage that produces strong reader-side joy/delight and was clearly written from the writer's pleasure rather than from plot necessity is allowed to stay, because the joy itself is non-trivial. The newspaper-office ad-takers becoming the things they are advertising is the worked instance. Treating joy-burst as a separate skill would name an exception without supplying a distinct procedure beyond "in this case, override Cornfeld")

- Chapter 15: The Door to the Truth Might Be Strangeness (Thoughts on "The Nose")
    - location: lines 5582-5588 (the absurdism-as-realism reframe: "Gogol is sometimes referred to as an absurdist, his work meant to communicate that we live in a world without meaning. But to me, Gogol is a supreme realist, looking past the way things seem to how they really are"; "Gogol says that we are, in our everyday perceptions, deceived. We feel, mostly, that our actions matter, and that earnest communication is happening, that we are real and permanent and in control of our fate. And under normal circumstances, these things are (mostly) true... But every now and then the scrim drops")
    - paraphrase: reframe absurdism as the deeper layer of realism; the strangeness in a Gogol-style story is not deviation from how things really work but a more honest depiction of how things really work, which everyday perception conceals
    - situation: a writer or critic is about to dismiss a strange-premise story as absurdist or unserious; the reframe is the corrective
    - outcome: → dropped because this is the dispositional / orientation framing that makes the strange-event-physics skill possible; it has no session-scope action distinct from "use the strange-event-physics skill." Folded as orienting context into psychological-physics-of-strangeness's "When to reach for this" rather than as its own skill

- Chapter 16: Afterthought #5
    - location: lines 5700-5712 (the student-paper anecdote: "Upon perusing this story, I felt myself at a distinct tilt"; Saunders riffs on the voice and arrives at the Privacy Tarps / Gender Areas world of "Jon"; "Just like that, a roomful of teenagers appeared, apparently horny... Needless to say, I had not thought to myself, 'I'd like to do a little something on the topic of how a group of confined teens deal with their powerful dawning sexuality.' I was just riffing on that sentence in the student paper, trying to sound 'like' that sentence"; "the path the story was on had narrowed"); lines 5722-5754 (the full follow-the-voice exposition: black-box framing of story as state-change device; the archery metaphor "stop aiming at the target and concentrate on the feeling of the arrow leaving the bow"; the imitating-uncles improv; the named method "following the voice"; the inspiration sources — real person, exaggerated tendency in self, fragment of language from elsewhere; the energy-of-the-voice imperative and the horse-as-novel-event escalation engine; the "Jon" Inarticulateness-dial procedure and "part surfer, part corporate wonk"; the chicken-and-egg of voice-leading-writer and writer-leading-voice; the beating-back of conceptions about "outcome" or "message"; "Jon" came to be "about" things "but none of that was intended at the beginning"; the generalization: "follow the voice" is one method, others are recurring imagery, words on page, sound, structural minutiae, "anything... about which she has strong opinions, she's less likely to know too well what she's doing")
    - paraphrase: when starting a story, do not begin from a theme, message, or outcome you want to deliver; begin from a fragment of voice (a real-person voice, an exaggerated tendency in yourself, a sentence from elsewhere), commit to sustaining/imitating it, and let the world emerge as a byproduct of what the voice forces; keep the voice generative by repeatedly putting new events in front of the character so the voice has to find new registers; the "outcome" is what arrives, not what you aimed at
    - situation: a writer is staring at a blank page and finds themselves trying to choose a topic, theme, or message; or a writer who knows what they want to "say" senses the resulting prose will read as a lecture or a one-sided performance; or a writer wants a method for getting out of "the plane of original conception" without having to pre-commit to a destination
    - outcome: → promoted to follow-the-voice

- Chapter 16: Afterthought #5
    - location: lines 5740-5742 (the voice-expansion-by-novel-events principle: "Having grasped the approximate 'rules' of the voice, the reader will get restless if subjected to a series of sentences that (merely) abide by those rules. So I have to keep finding new ways to make the person sound like himself. The best way to do this is to keep putting new events in front of him, events that are escalatory (new to him), so that he has to find new registers in his voice with which to respond. (If a character, talking along in a certain voice, has never seen a horse before, and I show him one, his voice has to expand, to accommodate the horse.)")
    - paraphrase: when a sustained voice is in danger of running in place (the reader has grasped the rules and the next sentences merely abide by them), introduce a new event the character has not yet encountered so the voice has to find a new register; the engine of voice-led drafting is escalatory-novelty
    - situation: drafting in a sustained voice and feeling the prose start to coast on the rules of the voice rather than to extend them
    - outcome: → folded into follow-the-voice (this is the escalation engine that keeps a voice-led draft generative; treating it as a separate skill would split the method from the engine that drives it. The horse example is the worked instance of the engine. Refuse-to-repeat-beats has a related shape — refuse to elaborate on a recently-arrived state — but its trigger is scene-pacing in revision, not voice-led drafting; the voice-expansion engine is the drafting-time form of the same anti-stasis principle, and it lives inside follow-the-voice)

- Chapter 16: Afterthought #5
    - location: lines 5762-5780 (the honey/milk passage from "Jon": Jon describes sex with Carolyn through TV ad LI 34321; "What he means is 'I really enjoyed that and I think I'm in love.' But he's feeling more than just that. And his voice is required, to tell us what else (what all) he's feeling"; "in that sentence, love has fallen on a particular, goofy person. Which is what love always falls on: a particular, goofy person"; the morning-walking-out passage: "the truth of that moment is more than just 'I walked out of my house one morning in June.' In that sentence, there's something missing, which is the 'I' walking out of the house. That morning has to fall on a certain mind for it to feel like any kind of real morning"; "voice is not just an embellishment; it's an essential part of the truth")
    - paraphrase: voice is not decoration on top of propositional content; it is the part of the prose that carries the felt truth that the propositional content does not reach. The reader experiences the gap between "I really enjoyed that and I think I'm in love" and what the character actually feels as truth, and only the voice can render that gap. Without the particular voice, the morning is no morning
    - situation: a writer is treating voice as a stylistic layer added to an underlying meaning that could in principle be paraphrased, and is producing prose whose "real" content is recoverable as a bare proposition
    - outcome: → folded into follow-the-voice (this is the orientation that licenses the method: voice is essential to truth, not embellishment, so following the voice is following the truth. Folded as orienting framing in the new skill's "When to reach for this" and the failure-mode section. The honey/milk and walking-out-the-house passages are the worked instances of the orientation. Treating it as a separate skill would name a disposition with no session-scope procedure distinct from the new skill's procedure)

- Chapter 16: Afterthought #5
    - location: lines 5722-5732 (the black-box framing: "We might imagine a story as a room-sized black box. The writer's goal is to have the reader go into that box in one state of mind and come out in another. What happens in there has to be thrilling and non-trivial"; "What is the exact flavor of the thrill? The writer doesn't have to know. That's what he's writing to find out"; the archery metaphor "stop aiming at the target and concentrate on the feeling of the arrow leaving the bow. In this alternate version of archery, the arrow then sails off in a certain direction and keeps adjusting course, and wherever it lands…that's the target"); lines 5790-5806 (the carnival-barker / engineer contrast and the roller-coaster designer: "If I think of a story as something that has to convey a certain message, as a train that has to pull into a certain station at a certain time, and myself as the stressed-out engineer trying to make that happen — it's too much. I freeze up and no fun is had"; "But if I imagine myself as a sort of genial carnival barker, trying to usher you into my magical black box, the workings of which even I don't fully understand — that, I can do"; the roller-coaster designer who "doesn't know or care much about the exact flavor of your reaction. What she really wants is for you to get your ass kicked at those places, then step out of that little car at the end so dazed and changed and happy that, for a few seconds, you've got nothing much to say")
    - paraphrase: the writer's stance toward the story should be barker-not-engineer: usher the reader into a state-changing apparatus whose workings even the writer doesn't fully understand, focus attention on the local craft (the curves and drops, the arrow leaving the bow), and let the destination announce itself; trying to know in advance the exact flavor of the reaction freezes the work
    - situation: a writer who is treating the story as a vehicle that must arrive at a particular meaning is freezing up; the corrective stance is to drop the destination-as-known and to attend to the local sentence-level work; the question shifts from "what does this story have to mean" to "what does this sentence delight me into doing next"
    - outcome: → folded into iterative-preference-revision (the existing skill names the anti-top-down stance and the locality of decision; this Afterthought adds three sharper metaphors — the black box, the archery release, the carnival barker / roller-coaster designer — that motivate the same stance. The roller-coaster designer's procedure ("focuses her attention on particular curves and drops... knows technically how to maximize the intensity at those places... doesn't know or care much about the exact flavor of your reaction") is exactly the iterative-preference-revision procedure restated with the apparatus-design analogy. Treating the black-box framing as a separate skill would name a disposition without supplying a distinct action; folding it adds the metaphors to the existing skill's failure-mode and orientation sections)

- Chapter 16: Afterthought #5
    - location: lines 5754 (the generalization: "But there are many methods. Each involves the writer proceeding in a way that honors or helps her pursue something about which she has strong opinions. It could be that she has strong opinions (is delighted by) patterns of recurring imagery. She might have strong opinions about the way the words look on the page. She might be a sound poet, guided by some obscure aural principle even she can't articulate. She might be obsessed with the minutiae of structure. It can be anything. The idea is that with her attention focused on that thing that delights her, about which she has strong opinions, she's less likely to know too well what she's doing and indulge in that knowing-in-advance that, as we've said, has a tendency to deaden a work and turn it into a lecture or a one-sided performance and drive the reader away")
    - paraphrase: "follow the voice" is one instance of a broader move — pick the thing about prose you have strong opinions about (voice, recurring imagery, the look of words on the page, sound, structure) and use that as the engine of the work, so you don't know in advance what the work is "about"
    - situation: a writer wants the broader principle of which "follow the voice" is a specific instance, to apply to writers who are not voice-led but image-led, sound-led, or structure-led
    - outcome: → folded into follow-the-voice (the broader principle is named in the new skill's "When to reach for this" as the abstract category, with voice as the worked instance and the other engines named explicitly. Treating it as its own skill would yield a near-tautological action ("identify what delights you, focus on it") with no observable signal beyond what the voice-led instance already provides)

